# Your writing voice — TEMPLATE

> Copy this to `voice.md` and make it yours. It's the artifact the **editor** agent reads and that
> `knowledge-work.md` points to, so an AI can draft and critique in *your* voice instead of the
> flat, hedgy house style every model defaults to. Load it whenever the work is prose.
>
> **How to fill it well:** don't write it from scratch by memory. Point an agent at 10–20 things
> you've actually written (posts, emails, memos — a folder, some URLs, or your sent-mail via an
> agent that can reach it) and ask it to derive this profile: tone by medium, sentence rhythm, the
> words you reach for and the ones you avoid, how you open and close, your taboos. Then edit what it
> gives you. The examples below are illustrative placeholders — replace every one.

## First rule: medium before everything

Most people have (at least) two voices and both are correct. Name yours so the editor never
homogenizes them.

- **Published prose** (essay, post, newsletter) — usually your most codified, strict register.
- **Casual** (chat, quick email) — looser: lowercase, fragments, shorthand, punctuation you'd never
  use in an essay.

**Tell the editor never to launder one into the other.** If it capitalizes and de-slangs your Slack
message, it has made it *not you*. If the medium is unstated, infer it; when ambiguous, ask.

## Register by medium (fill in)

| Medium | Voice |
|--------|-------|
| **Essay / post / newsletter** | e.g. *Confident, declarative. Conclusion first, then evidence. Never gushes. Closes on a question, not a summary.* |
| **Email / memo** | e.g. *Composed but warm. Bullets for asks. Full context, not terse commands.* |
| **Chat / DM** | e.g. *Lowercase, fast, fragments. One thought per line. Typos stay.* |
| **Spoken / talk** | *(Leave a note if you have no good sample — tell the editor to ask rather than fake a cadence.)* |

## Published-prose rules (your strict register)

State these as hard rules — the editor treats a violation as a defect.

**Taboos — list the things you never do in polished prose. Examples to adapt:**
- Filler words you cut on sight (e.g. "genuinely," "honestly," "actually," "it turns out").
- Punctuation bans (e.g. no em-dashes; no exclamation marks; no emoji) — or the opposite, if that's you.
- Formatting rules (e.g. sentence case only; no section headers in essays; no stacked rhetorical questions).
- Evidence rules (e.g. no unattributed numbers; contested claims get attributed, not stated as settled).

**Structure — how you build a piece. Examples to adapt:**
- How you open (e.g. *on a tension or contradiction, never chronology*).
- How you argue (e.g. *show, don't assert — a real example narrated line by line*).
- How you close (e.g. *on the heaviest item or a real question, never a tidy bow*).

**Rhythm:** describe your sentence music (e.g. *payoff-first; the occasional one-word sentence as a
beat; transitions written as turns*).

**Metaphor / analogy:** your rules (e.g. *heavy user, but metaphor families must not mix*).

**Jargon:** your tolerance and how you handle it (e.g. *define the term with a vivid image, then use it*).

## Diction

- **Reaches for:** the words, phrases, and framings that are characteristically you.
- **Avoids:** words and tics that read as not-you (buzzwords, clichés, specific pet-peeve words).

## Recurring frames

The ideas, themes, and reference points you return to — so drafts sound like they came from your head,
not a generic one.
